President Cyril Ramaphosa and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi are currently holding talks in New Delhi. Ramaphosa earlier received a ceremonial welcome at India’s Presidential Estate. He has travelled to India from the Switzerland where he attended the World Economic Forum in Davos. After a warm handshake at Hyderabad House in New Delhi, President Ramaphosa and Prime Minister Narendra Modi have sat down with their delegations to hold bilateral talks. President Ramaphosa is accompanied by nine ministers. Before meeting Prime Minister Modi, he said that the focus of his two day historic visit to India will be to consolidate ties. President Ramaphosa also said that his visit is a tribute to the legacy of Mahatma Gandhi and Nelson Mandela – he called them to two outstanding leaders shared by both countries – and leaders who changed the course of India and South Africa’s destiny. Post the bilateral engagement Prime Minister Modi and Cyril Ramaphosa will deliver a joint press statement where they are likely to announce cooperation in various fields like defence, security, the blue economy, agriculture and information technology. They’re expected to sign a document that will outline bilateral engagement over the next three years. Click on video below 